<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT"><font size=2>&nbsp;</font></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=2&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;2&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_1.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_1.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>ROBOCOP</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>24 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
We open this series with an oddity. <i>Robocop</i> was a slow-burner. The
original movie didn't stand out from the crowd when it was released in
1987, and it was so low-key that the computer game of the film was
planned to be released at the same time as the movie video release.
The coin-op manufacturers weren't too interested in the title at
first, leading to the odd situation where Ocean got the licence first
and Data East had to sublicence the arcade rights from Ocean when they
realised just what was on offer here.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=200 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d1_1988_ad17.png" target="1988_ad17.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d1_1988_ad17_small.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=293></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>A very understated ad campaign for <i>Robocop</i> - no double-page ad, just this simple frame from the movie.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>The pre-release news didn't grab me at all. Ocean already had a movie
game under their belt during 1988 with <i>Platoon</i>, and together with other
cinema-inspired offerings from the other software houses, I was
non-plussed with the whole concept. It was just another film licence.
Even the magazine preview spreads of the time implied that the game
wasn't anything special.
<TABLE ALIGN="center" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d1_1988_pre5.png" target="1988_pre5.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d1_1988_pre5_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=213></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Notice how <i>Robocop</i> is given equal billing to <i>Rambo III</i>? No one knew how big it was going to be.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/y1EUqPXoNno&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/y1EUqPXoNno&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Crash Robocop Demo</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Notice the rather nice boot-up sequence? Also everything gets killed by a single bullet - which would have made those three-way bullets <i>much</i> nicer to have in the finished game. <b><i>(4:29)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y1EUqPXoNno" target="y1EUqPXoNno">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
All that changed when Crash put a one-level playable demo on their
November 1988 issue. I was already fan of <i>Rolling Thunder</i>'s platform shooter
format, so when Robocop's warehouse level was given away for free, it
drew me in. The smooth graphics, large map, and the ability to aim
your gun to shoot at nasties on platforms above and below you had
improved on the <i>Rolling Thunder</i> formula immensely.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I was hooked, and took to replaying the level against the clock whilst
trying to beat it without getting hit by a single bullet. It's a good
reflection of the game that I put in the hours required in order to do
that. Eventually the magazines reviewed it, and Crash gave it a
three-page spread in their Christmas issue. I was sold on it,
immediately ordered a copy, and played it to death.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/YUVs7vXNZiw&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/YUVs7vXNZiw&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Full length Ariston TV advert</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">The <i>Robocop</i> theme tune was used in this rather clever advert for Ariston. The tune was taken from the Gameboy version and really was recorded just by connecting a tape recorder to a Gameboy's headphone socket! <b><i>(2:30)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YUVs7vXNZiw" target="YUVs7vXNZiw">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
It was one of those games which just kept on giving. As the nasties
attacked you in a set pattern, you were able to get further and
further into the game. There was also enough variety throughout the
levels to keep you interested, and a high enough difficulty level to
pose a serious challenge. It formed the template for future movie
conversions: multiple stages, various action stages (usually a man
running about slaughtering everything, with maybe an exploration
element thrown in), divided up with the odd puzzle level to spice
things up a bit.
<TABLE ALIGN="center" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d1_1988_rev2.png" target="1988_rev2.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d1_1988_rev2_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=218></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Crash goes all-out with a three-page review - a format restricted to the 1988 Christmas Special. Lots of padding, though.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
The tunes on the 128k version were well composed, and one of them
would even turn up as the soundtrack to a series of TV commercials for
Ariston ("And on. And on. And on. And Ariston.")
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For a game which had so little hype, it did staggeringly well.
Although it didn't dent the Top Ten for Christmas 1988 due to so many
other contenders that year, it went to #1 in January 1989 and
practically stayed there for the rest of the year. Even throughout
1990 it was still dipping in and out of the Top Ten, making it one of
the biggest selling Spectrum games of all time.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR><TR><TD><IMG SRC="chocs/voxpop.png" ALIGN="LEFT"><br><IMG SRC="pngs/gerard.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT"><TABLE BACKGROUND="/black7.png"><TR><TD><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#ffff00"><B><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;GERARD SWEENEY&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><br>
<b>We asked various well known and not so well known players in the Speccy scene from the past and present what their own ZXmas was like. First up is Gerard, part of the backbone of today's Speccy retroscene. Go for it Ger...</b><br><br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Who are you and what are you up to?</font></i></b><br>
I'm Gerard Sweeney.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In the real world, I'm a happily married father of twin boys (Hello, Jo, Matthew and Connor!), and work as a Senior ICT Technician for a local Council's Education dept.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In the far more enjoyable world <i>(OI! [THWACK!!] Jo)</i>, I run The Tipshop, and help out with World of Spectrum in a variety of ways - right now I rattle off emails/Facebook/LinkedIn messages to hundreds of unsuspecting individuals, asking if they were involved with a Speccy title 20+ years ago.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite cracker gift (aside from fortune-telling fish, naturally)?</font></i></b><br>
A bottle-opener key-ring in the shape of a hippo - it's been invaluable at get togethers. <TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/wHiuX2N63JQ&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/wHiuX2N63JQ&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>BBC1 Christmas Logo Montage</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">The perfect way to start this Advent Calendar - every BBC1 Christmas logo from 1974 through to 2007. You have my permission to drown yourself in festive nostalgia! <b><i>(6:28)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wHiuX2N63JQ" target="wHiuX2N63JQ">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Christmas Song?</font></i></b><br>
Always On My Mind, by Pet Shop Boys. (Who out there forgot this was a Xmas #1?)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best memory of Christmases gone by?</font></i></b><br>
On the record, the first Xmas with my boys.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Off the record, the Xmas I got my Speccy. I'd been asking Santa for it for months (cough), and just about shredded every present looking for it on Xmas Day.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It wasn't there, and I sat with a trembling lip. Shortly afterwards, my Dad asked me to get something out of the kitchen to find Santa had left it on the kitchen table by mistake (silly old Claus!).
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best Speccy Christmas memory?</font></i></b><br>
See above :)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Quality Street chocolate?</font></i></b><br>
To be honest, I don't know which one is which. I'm not fussy <i>(you mean you're a greedy bast? Ed)</i>.. Let's say ummm.. the purple one - whichever it is.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best present ever?</font></i></b><br>
See above :)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Speccy game you most looked forward to?</font></i></b><br>
<i>Operation Wolf</i> - and it didn't disappoint.
</TD></TR>
</TABLE><p>
